snippet.textDisplay:
You know... Having actually played the game, I have to applaud the level of (unintentional?) misrepresentation going on here. 
Like, nothing that's _said_ in the video is wrong... 

Meanwhile the gameplay footage playing in the background is deceptive as fuck. Because anyone who's actually played the game will recognise that most of the footage features as a massively over-leveled character with a health pool and equipment you wouldn't have until the mid-game, but running through the first area after the tutorial. 

At that point in the game you don't have things like the Aegis Arm (that little shield) or that big wrench yet, when you get hit by the enemies in that area at the point where you actually encounter them, they take off a third of your health, not a sliver, and they take three to five hits to down at that point, depending on which starting weapon you chose.

snippet.textDisplay: The gameplay is rubbish.  The bosses are just elaborate QTEs which you have to memorise.  What a joke !  Your build makes only a small difference to your combat success, all your time spent developing your character with buffs and trinkets is gameplay filler.  I've seen all types of combat on YouTube from players using different builds and nobody is OP.  Just watch how the post-stagger big combo has to be performed standing in the red circle.  WTF ?! The game is linear and totally scripted with player options just a ruse.  They should have had difficulty settings like so many other games.  At least the story is good.

snippet.textDisplay: If you like Dark Souls, this literally feels like it's from the same developer but with better graphics and a story that makes more sense as you go along.  It's as close to Dark Souls as you can get.  Everything down to the gameplay, leveling options, weapon buffs, and especially combat.  The difficulty is like a Dark Souls 3, not Elden Ring.  You may spend a couple hours on one boss instead of days.  I think it's a greatly balanced game that is fun, challenging, and also has a story that makes you think.

snippet.textDisplay: Looks great but I'm sick of games where you're expected to be ridiculously good and endlessly patient. I want to SEE the whole game, not just the first boss because the whole industry suddenly decided I need to "git good." I have other things to do, and I play games for fun, not out of some insecure need to prove my gaming prowess. Elden Ring, Dark Souls, Sekiro, Remnant of Ashes, and now Lies of P, all too arrogant and pretentious to provide difficulty levels. Such a shame; they look absolutely wonderful but hair tearing frustration and 2 days per boss is just not what I want to do with my time.
snippet.textOriginal: Looks great but I'm sick of games where you're expected to be ridiculously good and endlessly patient. This is one of the most unoriginal games I've ever played. Lies of P blatantly rips off of FromSoft's Soulsborne games so much that I began to hate it the further I progressed into my playthrough. It would be easier to list the things that Lies of P doesnâ€™t lift from FromSoftâ€™s games than it would be to list the things that it does.
If Lies of P didn't rip off so much from FromSoft's games, then it'd be an OK 7/10 experience for me, but I just can't get past that severe lack of originality.
I give this game a light 5 out of 10.

So far itâ€™s multiple times easier than fromsoft games. Stamina management can be careless, I can hack like 7-8 times before depleting and enemies usually die in 3-4 hits. Can pierce thru multiple enemies at once, they just line up. My attack animation starts way faster than the enemy. So if they are charging at me, I can just attack them first. Enemy attacks are very predictable with terrible range, most of the time donâ€™t even have to roll. Just back away is fine. Can parry easily and parry window is larger. 

But itâ€™s very fun so far. Love the atmosphere and mystery. Combat mechanics are a lot cooler than soulbourne, which makes it easier in turn I guess.

snippet.textDisplay: I actually really loved this game...but i was slightly disappointed with the end result...it felt premature when i got to the end. I have completed the game once and am running through again, but it felt like i wanted it to go a little deeper.everything almost felt too obligatory. Although i realize it is meant to be derivative in a flattering way...and it totally was, i wish it had a little more depth. I have to say though, for this studio's first foray into souls-likes, it was very well done as their budget wouldve been maxed for sure.

snippet.textDisplay:
im late to the party just got it this week on gamepass. im still on the last boss. 

at first the game felt clunky but i guess that was just the learning curve talking. now, i am absolutely inloved with the game. sure, it doesnt introduce a new groundbreaking mechanic. tbh i love that it took what works and integrated it together succesfully. 
red bar regen(bloodborne)
red power attacks undodgeble and unblockable(sekiro)
guard parry(sekiro)
etc. 
i love it all. the pacing is great, the world building hooks you, heck i was even invested with the side characters. ngl, there were some heart pulling moments too. 

cant wait to beat the last boss and see if i will play ng+(i never do)

I've heard purist say it's dumb and you end up spending more money on the sub than you would if you just bought the games, but I love how I can download some of these games, try them, and if I don't like them, I lose nothing. But I get to play tons of games that are amazing. 

I wish PS5 had a better version of it's system. I don't like the pay options. I like that I can just pay $15 a month and have all the game I want from Game Pass. PS needs to do a monthly option. Having to pay all at once for the year is annoying. Sure, it's one and done. But, it costs so much more that no everyone can budget that into their monthly payments. It's much easier to just pay $15 a month and be good.

snippet.textDisplay:
The parry/perfect guard system sucks. It's especially bad versus human targets that have basically instant attacks with no wind-up. It's pretty badly designed, imo. 

You also cannot use special combo attacks without getting interrupted, so those are pretty useless on average too since you have to use them during a stagger which costs the stagger attack window....so what's the point? Another bad system that should have given hyper armor to those abilities.

Everything else is cool.

snippet.textDisplay: As a souls vet whose beat Darks Souls 3, Elden Ring, and Dark Souls Remastered (each twice), I really love this game. It's probably the best loveletter to Souls games and a solid nod to Miyazaki and his team at Fromsoftware. After playing it for the past two days, I can say, the bosses are solid, challenging, and powered by casual tears (e.g., the Scrapped Watchman made me say a few colorful words and nearly made me throw my controller at the tv), the combat is smooth, and setting is absolutely gorgeous. I totally recommend playing this game.
snippet.textOriginal: As a souls vet whose beat Darks Souls 3, Elden Ring, and Dark Souls Remastered (each twice), I really love this game. It's probably the best loveletter to Souls games and a solid nod to Miyazaki and his team at Fromsoftware. After playing it for the past two days, I can say, the bosses are solid, challenging, and powered by casual tears (e.g., the Scrapped Watchman made me say a few colorful words and nearly made me throw my controller at the tv), the combat is smooth, and setting is absolutely gorgeous. I totally recommend playing this game.

Now have 12 hours in the game and I can honestly say it is now one of my all time favorites. snippet.textDisplay:
Was so certain I'd love this I broke my "no pre-orders" rule - for the second time this year (Armoured Core 6 being the other).

And I am not disappointed.
Love this game!

Find myself agreeing with another creator in that the perfect guard window could do with being a tiny bit larger - using his example, we're talking like if the window is 0.33s now, making it 0.5s.

This would better support the more Sekiro-like sequences where you're expected to chain multiple perfect guards.

He and I are both huge Souls fans, having sunk thousands of hours into FromSoft games, so this'd be more about expanding the utility of a core mechanic than being like "gAmE iS tOo HaRd pLs NeRf".

Whether they tweak this or not, though, it's gonna be me & this game from now till Lords of the Fallen drops ðŸ˜Ž

snippet.textDisplay: I love souls games but man I suck so bad.  But I love playing them, I beat Elden Ring and Bloodborne, though pretty sure Elden Ring was because it was open world.  I played the demo, and damn did I get absolutely destroyed.  With the dodge mechanic I felt like Wo Long all over again, had to sit there for hours grinding to try and perfect the parry mechanic, and then I was sliver away from beating the final demo boss and then I got destroyed, my spirit was crushed and i sat there for 6 hours trying to beat him.  But I am buying Lies of P, lets go another thousand rounds.  The accomplishment I feel from beating souls like games is amazing.  Like Elden Ring not only did I beat the game but I platinumed it on PS5, oh the joy of accomplishment.  So hopefully Lies of P will give me the same opportunity.

Beautiful game and a fair review - but probably not for me!
I feel this Victorian dystopia setting and slow pacing is getting a little bit over-used, maybe? I really enjoyed Surge 2, Armored Core 6, Star Wars Jedi - which are more fast paced 'souls-like' games set in futuristic and bright environments. I hope the developers would start imagining newer worlds.

snippet.textDisplay: My first Souls game was the Demon's Souls remake. I loved that game and managed to beat it without too much trouble. I then went straight to Sekiro and the combat instantly clicked, it's my favourite FromSoft game. I tried Elden Ring for about 15 hours but felt the open world didn't work, and found myself having to grinddddd for an hour every couple of hours to break even and that just wasn't fun. I was very excited for this game due to the art style, the world, their take on the source material etc but thought maybe I had my fill of Souls games. However, I played the demo for Lies of P and I absolutely loved it, so I'm very happy it's getting universally great reviews. Can't wait to play this day one!

snippet.textDisplay:
I've always wanted to get into these games because I think once I get some sort of hang of it, they'll have some of the best gaming/atmospheric moments you can find. Other than a 5-6 hr attempt at Bloodborne and playing the Souls-lites like Star Wars Jedi or Darksiders 3, I haven't tried these. Well, this demo has me giving it a real attempt now.

I was told by an online community that I'd be better off starting with Elden Ring, which is what I'm currently working my way through. Is it resolving all the confusing spec issues, etc.? No not really, but I am picking up some things here and there that I think will help me complete all of the FromSofts one day.

I did start Lies of P demo as the far right class for heavy attacks and now in Elden Ring I'm running a Confessor w/ more Dex. I still wish I was able to spec correctly and easily try different classes/attacking types. Still seems like once you spend those souls, you're committing in a too real way.

snippet.textDisplay: The thing I find funny about the "precision" argument in this sub-genre is that FS games were never particularly precise. People often argue this even when the game is actually, objectively more precise, if you were to slow it down and examine it frame by frame with input timestamps. Is it less precise? Or is it just not what you're used to from stanning FS for the last decade?
snippet.textOriginal: The thing I find funny about the "precision" argument in this sub-genre is that FS games were never particularly precise. People often argue this even when the game is actually, objectively more precise, if you were to slow it down and examine it frame by frame with input timestamps. Is it less precise? Or is it just not what you're used to from stanning FS for the last decade?

snippet.textDisplay: I love the art and setting of this game and had been looking forward to it since its first reveal. But then I tried the demo, and unfortunately, like with FromSoft games, I just really struggled playing it. I know it's a tired argument at this point, but I really wish that games like this would include more difficulty and accessibility options, because I really would love to play them. But even when I spend hours and hours playing and working at them, I never seem to get good enough to do what the game expects me to do, and it's very discouraging. I would love to play this or Bloodborne or Sekiro, but any time I've tried I always end up having to give up, and as a gamer, that's frustrating. I really wanted to play this one, and it sucks seeing another game with an art direction that I really enjoy go by without me yet again.

snippet.textDisplay: So I bought Bloodborne day one, and I still have the receipt in the case. At the time I had no clue who FromSoftware were. Needless to say, BB kicked my ass, and I put the game down cause it was too frustrating for me. Fast forward to 2023, and I finally made time for Bloodborne and The Old Hunters DLC. I became so addicted to it that earned the platinum, and every DLC trophy, and then I went out and bought Dark Souls trilogy, Nioh 1 and 2, Demons Souls remake, Elden Ring, Sekiro and a few others I can't remember the titles of right now lol I am beyond stoked for Lies of P as the overall aesthetic, and combat has me more excited than any other game coming out this year. Loving the Souls-like games now! Quick mention for another difficult game I highly recommend. Returnal. Play it! Easily one of my favorite PS5 games!

snippet.textDisplay: I'm happy they succeeded to make something slightly unique and different within the formula. Unfortunately, of all the Souls-like non-From games I've tried, they all fell flat in the end. The best Souls games are simply Souls games, Sekiro, Bloodborne and Elden Ring. They are just far beyond because they have an extremely unique vision with the best artists and creators in the world. Still, it's not fair to compare cream of the crop to this, and Lies of P clearly is an achievement of its own, and perhaps a couple of games in they can refine the formula. Hope they don't end up like Deck 13, though.
snippet.textOriginal: I'm happy they succeeded to make something slightly unique and different within the formula. Unfortunately, of all the Souls-like non-From games I've tried, they all fell flat in the end. The best Souls games are simply Souls games, Sekiro, Bloodborne and Elden Ring. They are just far beyond because they have an extremely unique vision with the best artists and creators in the world. Still, it's not fair to compare cream of the crop to this, and Lies of P clearly is an achievement of its own, and perhaps a couple of games in they can refine the formula. Hope they don't end up like Deck 13, though.

snippet.textDisplay:
Was looking forward to this game because I find the setting to be really interesting, and I had heard somewhere that while this game was soulsbourne inspired, it had the distinction of having adjustable difficulty options... I now realise I must`ve gotten that info mixed up with one of the more recent starwars games from EA, which is also darksould inspired, apparantly.

This is honestly a shame for me because I`m horrible at these types of games, and find their combat incredibly frustrating. I might give it a try at some point, but given what I`ve heard, the fact I`m fully into Starfield and The crew motorfest at the moment, and the massive backlog of gamas I want to get to at some point across several platforms, I really don`t think I`ll end up spending anywhere near as much time on the game as I was hoping, especially if the combat really is as chalanging and precise as described

Edit for anyone who may care: I decided to give this game a go, and while so far I only got as far as beating the first boss and getting to the hotel, I found what I`ve experienced of the game so far to be surprisingly engaging, and I found myself wanting to push though and beat that first boss, even though it gave atleast a good dozen thurough thrashings before I eventually managed to beat it, I found myself feeling less frustrated than I expected. This is especially surprising to me because I had been wanting to try Bloodbourne for years because of the setting, and when I finally did try it a while back, I found myself unable to even get to the first boss, and gave up after a few hours of what felt like me hitting my head against a wall a whole bunch. I would say that Lies of P is more newcomer friendly than Bloodborne, at least, and just as intriguing

snippet.textDisplay:
For those who didn't play the demo: The deflection works like Sekiro's, it doesn't disbalance the enemy for a riposte like in BB.

Standard block: recoverable hp loss (easy but costly)
Perfect guard: no hp loss and build enemy's nonvisible stagger meter. eg. When the Watchman boss does a chain attack, chain deflections are needed. 

This is the core part of the game and everything else is built around it. The nerfed roll during lock on is to encourage deflection.
